(Ollie barks)

06:24.696 --> 06:26.496
I know. I have to tell her.

06:26.498 --> 06:28.765
<i>While Sebastian</i>
<i>was feeling guilty,</i>

06:28.767 --> 06:32.469
<i>Samantha was feeling lucky.</i>

06:32.471 --> 06:34.337
Samantha, hey.

06:34.339 --> 06:38.074
Elliot.
Well, what a surprise.

06:38.076 --> 06:39.075
How are you?

06:39.077 --> 06:40.610
You know, hanging in.

06:40.612 --> 06:42.679
Well, good for you.
Hang in there, baby.

06:42.681 --> 06:43.913
I'm running a bit late, so...

06:43.915 --> 06:46.149
You gotta get in there
for a race?

06:46.151 --> 06:47.684
How do you know I'm here
to bet on a horse?

06:47.686 --> 06:49.986
We're in front of
the O.T.B.

06:49.988 --> 06:52.222
And a deli
and a hair center for men.

06:52.224 --> 06:54.457
You told me you
come up here and bet.

06:54.459 --> 06:56.893
I love the idea
that betting relaxes you.

06:56.895 --> 06:58.661
It did until you showed up.

06:58.663 --> 07:00.863
Look, I've been thinking
about you a lot.

07:00.865 --> 07:02.699
I was hoping to find you.
I don't know where you live.

07:02.701 --> 07:04.067
Very few people do.

07:04.069 --> 07:05.201
But...

07:05.203 --> 07:06.602
I needed to see you.

07:06.604 --> 07:10.606
So, I might've been hanging out
here in between my classes.

07:10.608 --> 07:13.109
N.Y.U. is 60 blocks away.

07:13.111 --> 07:15.178
Are you stalking me?

07:15.180 --> 07:17.280
Maybe?

07:17.282 --> 07:18.481
You're married.

07:18.483 --> 07:20.550
And I told you,
I can't see you.

07:20.552 --> 07:21.918
I know. I know.

07:21.920 --> 07:23.386
I don't understand
what's happening to me.

07:23.388 --> 07:26.155
I-I'm a scientist.
I know that sex

07:26.157 --> 07:27.890
is a purely physical act.

07:27.892 --> 07:30.293
But with you,
it's... it's more.

07:30.295 --> 07:31.794
It's like I crave you.

07:31.796 --> 07:35.798
I keep searching for this
biological explanation,

07:35.800 --> 07:37.166
but there's none.

07:38.635 --> 07:41.237
I don't know what to do.

07:41.239 --> 07:43.806
I do.

07:43.808 --> 07:46.242
Why don't we go inside
and bet on some horses?

07:46.244 --> 07:47.777
Maybe it'll relax you.

07:57.854 --> 08:00.656
(Under breath)
Keep your head down.

08:00.658 --> 08:01.924
And, Lyle!

08:01.926 --> 08:04.193
Get me that cappuccino machine.
I paid for it.

08:04.195 --> 08:05.628
Well, I borrowed it
from a photo shoot,

08:05.630 --> 08:06.595
so it's mine.

08:06.597 --> 08:08.364
Everything good?
What are you doing?

08:08.366 --> 08:09.331
Need help?

08:09.333 --> 08:10.699
What does it look like
I'm doing?

08:10.701 --> 08:11.800
I'm clearing out my desk.

08:11.802 --> 08:13.502
But why?

08:13.504 --> 08:15.604
Because I've been fired.

08:15.606 --> 08:17.373
From “Interview”?

08:17.375 --> 08:19.508
No, darling, from Charivari.

08:19.510 --> 08:21.210
Of course from “Interview”"

08:21.212 --> 08:22.544
what the hell happened?

08:22.546 --> 08:24.780
Andy's fragile ego happened.

08:24.782 --> 08:28.183
The wigged wonder can't handle
anybody else in the limelight!

08:28.185 --> 08:30.252
You didn't mention him
in the piece?

08:30.254 --> 08:33.856
I just got so carried away
talking about me,

08:33.857 --> 08:35.123
that I forgot.

08:35.125 --> 08:36.491
Anyway, screw him.

08:36.494 --> 08:37.960
I don't need him
or his magazine.

08:37.962 --> 08:40.629
Well, what will you do?

08:40.631 --> 08:42.431
I'll... plan my wedding.

08:42.433 --> 08:45.400
Redecorate the apartment,
buy art, sell art!

08:45.402 --> 08:47.035
I was in the arts section
of “the New York Times”

08:47.037 --> 08:48.770
I can do anything.

08:48.772 --> 08:50.973
Yes, you... you totally can.

08:50.975 --> 08:53.742
Um, so...

08:53.744 --> 08:56.611
What will this,
uh, mean for me?

08:56.613 --> 08:58.313
Who will I be working for next?

08:58.315 --> 08:59.915
Oh, darling.
You're fired, too.

08:59.917 --> 09:02.884
When you hitch your wagon
to a star, well, you know.

09:02.886 --> 09:04.086
You fall when they do?

09:04.088 --> 09:06.788
I wouldn't exactly
say “fall.”

09:06.790 --> 09:09.691
but, yeah. In a nutshell.
(Object clatters)

09:09.693 --> 09:11.059
(Sighs)

09:16.788 --> 09:19.037
But if I-I could just
explain my... my situation,

09:19.157 --> 09:21.157
I think you... I-I am truly sorry, Ms.
Bradshaw.

09:21.159 --> 09:22.926
But unfortunately,
matriculating at N.Y.U.

09:22.928 --> 09:24.594
This fall is not an option.

09:24.596 --> 09:26.162
There are no slots.

09:26.164 --> 09:27.931
But you accepted me.
(Drawer closes)

09:27.933 --> 09:30.166
And you turned us down.

09:30.168 --> 09:32.369
Yes, but that was before
my circumstances had changed.

09:32.371 --> 09:34.437
You wanted me a month ago.
Don't you want me now?

09:34.439 --> 09:35.839
I'm a... I'm a really
hard worker.

09:35.841 --> 09:37.474
I am truly sorry, sweetie.

09:37.476 --> 09:39.709
But we went to
the wait-list last week.

09:39.711 --> 09:41.578
So I missed my shot by a week?

09:41.580 --> 09:42.912
Three days, actually.

09:42.914 --> 09:44.781
What should I do?

09:44.783 --> 09:49.152
Look, you... you can sit down
with the head of admissions

09:49.154 --> 09:50.787
and plead your case.

09:50.789 --> 09:52.188
Okay, great.

09:52.190 --> 09:53.556
And then maybe
you'll get in for spring,

09:53.558 --> 09:54.924
definitely for next year.

09:54.926 --> 09:59.228
Well, what am I supposed
to do for the next seven months?

09:59.230 --> 10:02.065
Get a job?

10:02.067 --> 10:03.466
Well, that's what caused

10:03.468 --> 10:05.635
this whole mess
in the first place.

10:05.637 --> 10:08.905
(Samantha and Elliot moaning
and breathing heavily)

10:16.947 --> 10:19.248
Well, that was a mistake.

10:19.250 --> 10:22.118
Oh. Is that what
a mistake sounds like?

10:22.120 --> 10:23.819
I always confuse that
with an orgasm.

10:23.821 --> 10:27.690
I meant that I had
the orgasm with you.

10:27.692 --> 10:30.626
There's nothing wrong
with what we're doing.

10:30.628 --> 10:33.195
I'm in an open marriage.
(Zips pants)

10:33.197 --> 10:34.497
Does your wife know
you stalked me?

10:34.499 --> 10:37.533
I prefer “Hang around
where you might be."

10:37.535 --> 10:39.969
Or that you think
about me all the time?

10:39.971 --> 10:42.071
No.

10:42.073 --> 10:44.740
Or that I think about you
all the time?

10:44.742 --> 10:45.841
You do?

10:45.843 --> 10:48.310
Look, I admit that
this is confusing,

10:48.312 --> 10:49.845
but I don't want to let you go.

10:49.847 --> 10:53.149
Well, too bad, buddy,
'cause I am outta here.

10:53.151 --> 10:54.550
I don't do commitment,

10:54.552 --> 10:57.019
especially not with someone
who's already committed.

10:57.021 --> 11:00.856
My mom did that enough
for the both of us.

11:00.858 --> 11:02.224
Well, Elliot...

11:02.226 --> 11:03.726
it was nice to see you,

11:03.728 --> 11:06.061
and I hope I never
have the pleasure again.

11:06.063 --> 11:07.730
Wait, wait, I...
I know what you're doing.

11:07.732 --> 11:08.864
Leaving.

11:08.866 --> 11:10.766
You're trying to run
away from me.

11:10.768 --> 11:12.868
I'm just trying to walk out
of your apartment.

11:12.870 --> 11:14.470
No, it's a biological
imperative.

11:14.472 --> 11:15.971
When the body has
an adrenaline rush,

11:15.973 --> 11:18.407
it stimulates your desire
for fight or flight.

11:18.409 --> 11:19.742
It's totally natural.

11:19.744 --> 11:21.643
Well, if it's totally natural,
then bye-bye I fly.

11:21.645 --> 11:24.279
You don't have to race
out of here.

11:24.281 --> 11:25.747
(Sighs)

11:25.749 --> 11:27.950
You could stay and fight.

11:27.952 --> 11:31.687
Or... not fight.

11:31.689 --> 11:33.589
Honey...

11:33.591 --> 11:36.491
It's better if I run
because when I fight,

11:36.493 --> 11:39.761
well, it can get ugly.

11:42.398 --> 11:45.434
What time is your bus?

11:45.436 --> 11:46.535
At 4:00.

11:46.537 --> 11:49.404
Mm. So we only have
three more hours together.

11:49.406 --> 11:51.506
I miss you already.

11:51.508 --> 11:53.108
Same.

11:53.110 --> 11:54.843
But just think, in the fall
when I'm at C.C.S.U.,

11:54.845 --> 11:56.611
we'll only be 20 minutes
from each other.

11:57.880 --> 11:59.047
Can you stay in my dorm?

11:59.049 --> 12:00.515
I'm not sure.

12:00.517 --> 12:01.516
And I know I can't stay
in the barracks,

12:01.518 --> 12:03.084
although that would
be interesting.

12:03.086 --> 12:06.054
(Laughs) Mags, you're too much.

12:06.056 --> 12:07.756
Look, let's not
worry about that.

12:07.758 --> 12:09.658
We've got months
to figure that out.

12:09.660 --> 12:11.960
Yeah. Of course.

12:11.962 --> 12:13.795
You know what? I gotta go
hit the men's room.

12:13.797 --> 12:16.031
You wanna grab the checks?
We can head out, take a walk

12:16.033 --> 12:17.999
or... something.

12:18.001 --> 12:19.601
I like the sound of something.
(Chuckles)

12:19.603 --> 12:21.136
Hey, do you have any chapstick?

12:21.138 --> 12:23.638
Yeah, it's in my jacket.

12:36.986 --> 12:39.988
Hey!
How was your first day?

12:39.990 --> 12:41.356
(Door closes) Guess you're
doing such a good job

12:41.358 --> 12:42.524
they're letting you
leave early.

12:42.526 --> 12:45.526
I didn't get to do
my job at all.

12:45.528 --> 12:46.661
I got fired.

12:46.663 --> 12:47.795
What?

12:47.797 --> 12:49.097
Or more specifically,
Larissa was fired,

12:49.099 --> 12:51.633
and then I was just
swept out with the trash.

12:51.635 --> 12:54.135
And then I went to N.Y.U.
and found out

12:54.137 --> 12:56.204
that fall's not an option
either.

12:56.206 --> 12:57.872
Why didn't you call me? I did.

12:57.874 --> 12:59.407
You didn't answer.

12:59.409 --> 13:01.576
Oh, I must've been
walking Ollie.

13:01.578 --> 13:04.512
So what have you been
doing for the last few hours?

13:04.514 --> 13:06.447
Just wandering around in shock.

13:06.449 --> 13:09.050
I thought about drinking
myself into oblivion,

13:09.052 --> 13:11.786
but then I decided,
who wants to drink alone?

13:11.788 --> 13:12.920
So you wanna drink?

13:12.922 --> 13:15.790
- It's 3:00.
- So that's a no?

13:18.327 --> 13:20.428
Uh, maybe we should talk
before we drink.

13:20.430 --> 13:21.796
What is there to say?

13:21.798 --> 13:24.665
Well, I've been trying
to figure out a way

13:24.667 --> 13:26.100
to tell you something.

13:26.102 --> 13:29.270
- Something kinda big.
- Okay.

13:29.272 --> 13:34.942
And I haven't known how because,
well, your... your life is here.

13:34.944 --> 13:37.178
Well, not anymore.
There's nothing for me here.

13:37.180 --> 13:39.013
The city has officially
turned on me.

13:39.015 --> 13:40.381
Maybe that isn't a bad thing.

13:40.383 --> 13:42.783
Maybe it would leave you open
to other opportunities.

13:42.785 --> 13:44.218
Like what?

13:44.220 --> 13:46.120
Because I still think drinking
the day away is a good one.

13:46.122 --> 13:48.422
(Chuckles) So I've been
mulling around

13:48.424 --> 13:51.425
with the idea of moving
to Malibu for the company.

13:51.427 --> 13:54.128
I-I need to be there to see
if this investment

13:54.130 --> 13:55.229
could be something.

13:55.231 --> 13:58.265
Just for the summer.
Maybe for longer.

13:58.267 --> 13:59.833
So you'd leave Manhattan?

13:59.835 --> 14:02.603
I haven't wanted to because
I don't wanna leave you.

14:02.605 --> 14:04.571
But maybe now
I wouldn't have to.

14:04.573 --> 14:05.806
You could come with me.

14:05.808 --> 14:07.041
To California?

14:07.043 --> 14:08.042
For a few months.

14:08.044 --> 14:10.177
You could take walks
on the beach.

14:10.179 --> 14:11.845
I-I could teach you
to surf.

14:11.847 --> 14:14.348
It would be
an amazing adventure.

14:14.350 --> 14:16.250
Lots of material
for your writing.

14:16.252 --> 14:18.185
And we could be doing it
together.

14:18.187 --> 14:20.287
So what do you say?

14:28.555 --> 14:29.922
(Samantha) Whoo-hoo!

14:29.924 --> 14:31.390
(Singsongy)
We're going to Cali!

14:31.392 --> 14:33.726
Are you using the royal “We”?
Because I'm pretty sure

14:33.728 --> 14:37.163
I just said <i> I'm</i> going
to Malibu with Sebastian.

14:37.165 --> 14:38.698
Wouldn't you want
a friend there?

14:38.700 --> 14:41.467
I could keep some of Sebastian's
hot surfer boys company.

14:41.469 --> 14:43.335
(Singsongy) I wouldn't
want them to get lonely.

14:43.337 --> 14:44.970
Why would you leave the city?

14:44.972 --> 14:47.039
Because I'm a nomad.
And when the need comes,

14:47.041 --> 14:48.874
nomads move on
to greener pastures.

14:48.876 --> 14:50.342
Or bluer oceans.

14:50.344 --> 14:53.145
It's really that easy for you
to just pick up and move?

14:53.147 --> 14:55.047
Not just easy.
Essential.

14:55.049 --> 14:56.148
Well...
(Chopsticks snap)

14:56.150 --> 14:57.216
I hate moves.

14:57.218 --> 14:59.385
That's because you hold on
to too much.

14:59.387 --> 15:00.352
It's because I hold
so many things

15:00.354 --> 15:01.921
and so many people very dear.

15:01.923 --> 15:03.556
Well,
that's your first mistake.

15:03.558 --> 15:06.125
At the first sign of trouble,
you have to be ready to run.

15:06.127 --> 15:08.527
Hey, there's nothing wrong
with running away.

15:08.529 --> 15:11.897
It's in our D.N.A.
It's actually a safety valve.

15:11.899 --> 15:13.465
At least that's what
Elliot says.

15:13.467 --> 15:16.268
(Gasps) So you saw Elliot.

15:16.270 --> 15:19.405
Is that why you're suddenly
talking about moving?

15:19.407 --> 15:21.840
I might've... accidentally
slept with him.

15:21.842 --> 15:24.476
How does that
accidentally happen?

15:24.478 --> 15:28.213
He stalks you in actually
a cute and romantic way,

15:28.215 --> 15:29.848
and then you fall for it,
and then you think,

15:29.850 --> 15:31.950
“Yikes, I gotta get
out of here.”

15:31.952 --> 15:34.853
so less accident
and more train wreck.

15:34.855 --> 15:36.955
You don't have to move!
It's a big city.

15:36.957 --> 15:38.156
Look, this might be
hard for you to see

15:38.158 --> 15:40.759
because your life's
always been about stability.

15:40.761 --> 15:42.094
Not anymore.

15:42.096 --> 15:45.197
But for me, running has always
brought me to better places.

15:45.199 --> 15:47.799
The first time I ran away
from home to get away

15:47.801 --> 15:49.601
from my mom and one
of her deadbeat boyfriends,

15:49.603 --> 15:50.836
I wound up in Miami

15:50.838 --> 15:52.471
working at one
of the hottest clubs in town.

15:52.473 --> 15:56.942
Well, maybe there's nothing
for you to escape from now.

15:56.944 --> 15:58.310
How I feel about Elliot?

15:58.312 --> 16:01.279
Well, how exactly
<i>do</i> you feel about Elliot?

16:01.281 --> 16:04.149
Scared. Excited.

16:04.151 --> 16:06.218
Vulnerable.

16:06.220 --> 16:08.553
- Well, you can't run away from that.
- Sure, I can.

16:08.555 --> 16:10.822
I don't acknowledge it,
then it'll just go away.

16:10.824 --> 16:13.291
So if I never tell my dad
that I lost my job,

16:13.293 --> 16:15.760
and I'm moving to Malibu,
that will go away?

16:15.762 --> 16:18.096
See? Running and hiding
has its appeal.

16:18.098 --> 16:20.699
Mmm, yeah, it does.

16:22.668 --> 16:25.337
(Chuckles) Well,
look at the little lovebirds.

16:25.339 --> 16:27.739
Tommy, my friend, we are.

16:27.741 --> 16:29.274
I cannot wait
to marry this woman...

16:29.276 --> 16:31.409
So much so we're moving
the wedding up.

16:31.411 --> 16:33.011
Oh, it's two weeks from Friday.

16:33.013 --> 16:35.280
(Singsongy) So mark that day
in your calendar.

16:35.282 --> 16:37.115
Mm. It will be a day
that goes down in infamy.

16:37.117 --> 16:38.983
So I guess you decided
against a big wedding?

16:38.985 --> 16:40.919
(Scoffs) Are you high
on crack cocaine?

16:40.921 --> 16:43.555
A small wedding?
Why would we even bother?

16:43.557 --> 16:46.391
Well, I just assumed
since it was so soon that...

16:46.393 --> 16:47.892
It's going to be ginormous.
It's going to be over the top

16:47.894 --> 16:49.627
and totally inappropriate.

16:49.629 --> 16:50.795
That's my baby.

16:50.797 --> 16:52.597
Mmm. (Kisses)

16:52.599 --> 16:54.799
And since I'm not
at “Interview” anymore,

16:54.801 --> 16:57.168
I can use all of my talents
and focus and energy

16:57.170 --> 16:59.137
to make sure no one in this town
talks of anything else

16:59.139 --> 17:00.371
for the rest of the year.

17:00.373 --> 17:03.007
Wait, you're... not
at “Interview” anymore?

17:03.009 --> 17:05.410
Oh, Tom, I feel absolutely
horrible for Carrie.

17:05.412 --> 17:07.744
And I promise you, I will try
to help her find a job.

17:07.747 --> 17:10.281
I mean, after I finish planning
our wedding, our honeymoon.

17:10.282 --> 17:12.383
I hope the fact that Andy
blackballed me from publishing

17:12.385 --> 17:13.550
doesn't hurt her.

17:13.553 --> 17:14.819
Carrie lost her job?

17:14.820 --> 17:17.954
She didn't tell you?

17:19.458 --> 17:21.325
<i>♪</i>

17:21.327 --> 17:22.460
(Maggie) So what do you think?

17:22.462 --> 17:24.494
What <i> kind</i> of napkin?

17:24.497 --> 17:26.030
What difference does that make?

17:26.031 --> 17:28.666
Well, if it's from Hooters,
he's definitely cheating.

17:28.668 --> 17:30.968
If it's a cocktail napkin,
he's thinking about cheating,

17:30.970 --> 17:32.870
and if it's
a paper dinner napkin,

17:32.872 --> 17:35.239
well, he took her
someplace cheap.

17:35.241 --> 17:36.941
But he's still cheating.
(Groans)

17:36.943 --> 17:39.110
- The name on the napkin was Jess, right?
- Right.

17:39.112 --> 17:40.544
Maybe it's a guy.

17:40.546 --> 17:41.779
(Laughs) Even weirder.

17:41.781 --> 17:44.048
Oh, my God.
Am I dating another gay guy

17:44.050 --> 17:46.484
and I don't even know it?
Is that my thing?

17:46.486 --> 17:48.119
I don't get a gay vibe
from him at all.

17:48.121 --> 17:50.488
Pete is a great guy,
Maggie, and he loves you.

17:50.490 --> 17:51.722
And it's not like something
in the last week

17:51.724 --> 17:52.957
would've changed that.

17:52.959 --> 17:54.492
Have you been acting
at all desperate and needy?

17:54.494 --> 17:57.294
I.E., like yourself?
Guys run from that.

17:57.296 --> 17:58.696
He did start acting
kind of strange

17:58.698 --> 17:59.964
when I started talking

17:59.966 --> 18:01.198
about what our lives would be
like in the fall.

18:01.200 --> 18:03.901
Uhh. Case closed.
You scared him off.

18:03.903 --> 18:07.237
You didn't ask him specifics
like what days you'd be together

18:07.239 --> 18:09.239
or how'd you be together?

18:09.241 --> 18:11.075
I may have brought it up
a couple times this week.

18:11.077 --> 18:12.543
Oy.

18:12.545 --> 18:14.078
I'm sorry, but those are
important questions.

18:14.080 --> 18:15.879
Not three months out!

18:15.881 --> 18:17.548
Yeah. I agree with Donna.
Kinda scary.

18:17.550 --> 18:20.918
So I ran another guy off
with my desperation? Great.

18:20.920 --> 18:22.853
I'm gonna be alone forever.

18:22.855 --> 18:24.688
I think you should just
talk to Pete.

18:24.690 --> 18:26.123
Maybe it's not what we think.

18:26.125 --> 18:27.724
Maybe there's
a good explanation.

18:27.726 --> 18:29.459
But just to be safe,
I'd wear waterproof mascara.

18:29.461 --> 18:32.629
I'm guessing there could be
a few tears.

18:32.631 --> 18:34.965
(Knock on door)

18:34.967 --> 18:37.134
<i>They say you can run...</i>

18:40.605 --> 18:43.674
<i>But you can't hide.</i>

18:43.676 --> 18:45.609
Dad?

18:51.071 --> 18:55.207
So I decided to go to Malibu.

18:55.209 --> 18:58.377
Um, probably just
for a few months.

18:58.379 --> 19:01.380
Maybe a little longer.

19:06.119 --> 19:09.521
I'm done here, Carrie.

19:09.523 --> 19:11.290
I don't know what to say.

19:11.292 --> 19:13.992
Well, you could say
you support my decision.

19:13.994 --> 19:15.594
But that would be a lie.

19:15.596 --> 19:18.430
Well, can we at least
talk about this?

19:18.432 --> 19:19.832
No.

19:19.834 --> 19:22.801
You know how I feel about
the decision that got you here

19:22.803 --> 19:25.204
and the choice that
you're making now.

19:25.206 --> 19:30.175
But you are 18 years old,
and I can't stop you.

19:30.177 --> 19:32.444
So when are you leaving
for California?

19:32.446 --> 19:36.515
Um, after Larissa's wedding.

19:39.085 --> 19:41.353
I guess we can say
our good-byes then.

19:49.929 --> 19:51.797
(Door closes) <i> It's hard
to know in this world</i>

19:51.799 --> 19:55.000
<i>if you're running towards</i>
<i>or away from something.</i>

19:55.002 --> 19:59.371
<i>The markers, the milestones</i>
<i>look the same either way.</i>

19:59.373 --> 20:01.406
<i>So how do we know</i>
<i>if we're moving forward</i>

20:01.408 --> 20:03.642
<i>or just moving?</i>

20:03.644 --> 20:07.479
<i>And for some reason,</i>
<i>I was moved to come here...</i>

20:07.481 --> 20:10.615
<i>to Weaver's.</i>

20:10.617 --> 20:11.850
Carrie.

20:11.852 --> 20:13.451
<i>While I was reaching out</i>
<i>to someone meaningful</i>

20:13.453 --> 20:14.919
<i>from my past,</i>

20:14.921 --> 20:16.788
<i>Maggie was hoping</i>
<i>she wasn't about to</i>

20:16.790 --> 20:19.591
<i>reach out to someone</i>
<i>meaningful to Pete's present.</i>

20:19.593 --> 20:21.059
I thought you were going
to talk to Pete.

20:21.061 --> 20:22.560
I am. (Sighs)

20:22.562 --> 20:24.763
Right after I hear
this bitch-slut's voice.

20:24.765 --> 20:26.064
What if it's a guy?

20:26.066 --> 20:27.232
Well, then I can stop
freaking out

20:27.234 --> 20:28.733
and spending
my every waking moment

20:28.735 --> 20:31.035
figuring out how I'm gonna
tear this bitch-slut cooze

20:31.037 --> 20:32.136
limb from limb.

20:32.138 --> 20:33.538
Maggie...

20:33.540 --> 20:34.606
You agreed.
Talking to Pete...

20:34.608 --> 20:36.074
(Line ringing)
Shh, it's ringing.

20:36.076 --> 20:37.108
(Woman) Hello?

20:37.110 --> 20:38.209
(Whispers) Say something.
(Whispers) No!

20:38.211 --> 20:40.178
Say something. Say... no!

20:40.180 --> 20:43.581
(Exhales)
Hi. Is Jess there?

20:43.583 --> 20:44.682
This is she.

20:44.684 --> 20:47.752
It's a friend of Pete's.
Do you know him?

20:47.754 --> 20:48.987
Pete O'Malley? (Chuckles)

20:48.989 --> 20:51.055
Don't be silly.
Of course I know him.

20:51.057 --> 20:52.757
(Whispers) Ask how well.

20:52.759 --> 20:53.891
How well?

20:53.893 --> 20:55.059
I'm sorry?

20:55.061 --> 20:57.061
How well do you know Pete?

20:57.063 --> 21:01.132
I... well...
(Line disconnects, dial tone)

21:01.134 --> 21:04.569
Did she just hang up?

21:04.571 --> 21:06.237
(Hangs up receiver)

21:07.339 --> 21:09.907
So it sounds like you've
made a really good decision.

21:09.909 --> 21:12.109
I hear great things
about Malibu.

21:12.111 --> 21:13.311
I think so.

21:13.313 --> 21:15.580
I'm trying to envision myself
as Joan Didion,

21:15.582 --> 21:17.181
stepping away from the city

21:17.183 --> 21:18.950
so I can find
the space to write.

21:18.952 --> 21:20.451
Yeah, I'm not like that.

21:20.453 --> 21:23.154
I need the crush of people
to inspire me.

21:23.156 --> 21:25.189
What? Are you worried
about going?

21:25.191 --> 21:28.826
Well, Samantha says
I'm not good at change.

21:28.828 --> 21:30.494
But I guess who is?

21:30.496 --> 21:32.296
(Chuckles) Samantha?

21:32.298 --> 21:35.065
Yeah, she can definitely
roll with the punches.

21:35.067 --> 21:36.967
I'm not sure I can.

21:36.969 --> 21:38.969
I think that's why
I'm so hesitant.

21:38.971 --> 21:40.905
Is that why you came to see me?

21:40.907 --> 21:43.541
You looking for someone
to tell you not to go?

21:43.543 --> 21:45.709
No. I have my dad
for that.

21:45.711 --> 21:49.079
I guess I just wanted
someone's honest opinion.

21:49.081 --> 21:51.615
And I can't talk to
Sebastian about it.

21:51.617 --> 21:53.117
I don't want him to think

21:53.119 --> 21:55.319
I'm having doubts
because of him.

21:55.321 --> 21:56.654
Because I'm... I'm not.

21:56.656 --> 21:57.988
But you are having doubts.

21:57.990 --> 21:59.990
Well, yeah, it's a big move.

21:59.992 --> 22:04.328
I mean, what's gonna happen
to me? To my writing?

22:04.330 --> 22:06.663
You're talented
wherever you are.

22:06.665 --> 22:09.199
A zip code isn't gonna
change that.

22:09.201 --> 22:11.535
You were a huge part of me

22:11.537 --> 22:14.304
becoming who I am as a writer.

22:14.306 --> 22:15.806
You challenged me.

22:15.808 --> 22:19.910
But you also took me seriously
and helped me own my writing.

22:19.912 --> 22:22.012
I think you give me
way too much credit.

22:22.014 --> 22:23.680
(Laughs)
(Laughs)

22:23.682 --> 22:26.883
But if it means you
think of me every now and again,

22:26.885 --> 22:28.518
I'll take it.

22:28.520 --> 22:31.488
Yeah.

22:31.490 --> 22:33.090
Well, you were my first.

22:33.092 --> 22:36.026
So you'll always hold
a special place

22:36.028 --> 22:38.395
in this kooky brain of mine.

22:38.397 --> 22:40.897
Good.

22:40.899 --> 22:45.035
And if you decide to,
you know, come...

22:45.037 --> 22:48.171
or decide not to go at all...

22:48.173 --> 22:49.673
I'm here.

22:49.675 --> 22:52.317
Just a phone call away.

22:55.413 --> 22:58.415
So... how was work today?

22:58.417 --> 23:01.418
Fine.

23:01.420 --> 23:04.688
Anything interesting happen?

23:04.690 --> 23:07.424
Yeah. My youngest daughter
was being nice to me.

23:07.426 --> 23:09.359
Really?
What was that like?

23:09.361 --> 23:10.560
It was kind of scary.

23:10.562 --> 23:13.496
(Sighs) Not so fun
for me either.

23:13.498 --> 23:17.233
Look, I promised Carrie
I would be nice to you.

23:17.235 --> 23:18.701
Well, I wouldn't worry
about it.

23:18.703 --> 23:20.804
It's not like Carrie's so good
at keeping her word.

23:20.806 --> 23:23.006
Dad...

23:23.008 --> 23:25.108
Carrie didn't promise you
anything.

23:25.110 --> 23:27.377
She never promised you college

23:27.379 --> 23:28.878
or staying close by.

23:28.880 --> 23:32.515
I felt like we had a deal.

23:32.517 --> 23:34.350
She knew what was expected
of her.

23:34.352 --> 23:36.119
It wasn't a promise,

23:36.121 --> 23:38.221
but...

23:38.223 --> 23:40.623
I trusted her to do
the right thing,

23:40.625 --> 23:42.125
and she broke that trust.

23:42.127 --> 23:44.560
Because she isn't making
the choices you would make?

23:46.864 --> 23:50.266
It's always been hard for me
that you and Carrie

23:50.268 --> 23:51.768
have so much in common.

23:51.770 --> 23:54.137
But now I realize
it's been easier on me

23:54.139 --> 23:56.606
because you don't expect
so much from me.

23:56.608 --> 23:59.575
Dorrit, that is not true.
I want so much for you.

23:59.577 --> 24:01.344
Yeah, but you don't expect me

24:01.346 --> 24:03.446
to want the same things
you want.

24:04.648 --> 24:06.816
So why do you expect that
from Carrie?

24:10.487 --> 24:13.389
<i>While Dorrit was giving my dad</i>
<i>something to think about,</i>

24:13.391 --> 24:17.660
<i>Mouse and West were being given</i>
<i>the gift of encyclopedias.</i>

24:17.662 --> 24:20.596
Whoa! These are
the really fancy kind.

24:20.598 --> 24:23.466
Wait. I think this box only
has half the alphabet.

24:24.468 --> 24:27.770
Mine, too. Where are
the other boxes?

24:27.772 --> 24:30.106
They must not have accounted
for two valedictorians.

24:30.108 --> 24:33.609
So... what do we do now?

24:33.611 --> 24:35.478
You two are Castlebury's
best and brightest.

24:35.480 --> 24:37.479
I'm sure you'll come up
with a compromise.

24:37.481 --> 24:39.715
Uh, but, Mister... ugh.

24:39.717 --> 24:43.319
What are we supposed
to do with one gift?

24:48.491 --> 24:50.559
(Latches click)

24:50.561 --> 24:53.662
(Sighs) This place looks so...

24:53.664 --> 24:55.130
Empty.

24:55.132 --> 24:58.967
I was gonna say “sad,”

24:58.969 --> 25:01.904
it's weird to think someone else
will be living here.

25:01.906 --> 25:03.972
Has Larissa found anyone
to move in?

25:03.974 --> 25:07.576
Not yet. I think
she's trying to decide

25:07.578 --> 25:10.512
whether it's actually time to let it go.
(Suitcase thuds)

25:10.514 --> 25:12.414
I don't know how
she ever could. (Chuckles)

25:12.416 --> 25:15.651
Wait until you see the view
from the cliffs at Point Dume.

25:15.653 --> 25:17.920
It'll make leaving here
a lot easier.

25:17.922 --> 25:19.321
I talked to Shane today.

25:19.323 --> 25:21.523
He said Ollie is
loving the beach.

25:21.525 --> 25:22.724
Oh.

25:22.726 --> 25:24.092
And most of our stuff arrived.

25:24.094 --> 25:25.560
“Our stuff”"

25:25.562 --> 25:28.173
Mmm.
I like the sound of it.

25:28.293 --> 25:29.404
Me, too.

25:29.524 --> 25:30.415
Mm.

25:30.535 --> 25:32.097
You ready?

25:33.469 --> 25:35.003
Yeah.

25:36.706 --> 25:39.407
<i>In that moment, I wondered</i>
<i>why we say good-bye</i>

25:39.409 --> 25:41.743
<i>when we leave something</i>
<i>we love.</i>

25:43.312 --> 25:44.579
<i>Because most often,</i>

25:44.581 --> 25:46.982
<i>the parting feels painful</i>
<i>and sad.</i>

25:46.984 --> 25:49.211
<i>There's nothing good about it.</i>

25:49.331 --> 25:50.864
We should go.

25:50.984 --> 25:52.554
We don't wanna be late
for the wedding.

25:54.557 --> 25:56.224
Good-bye.

26:07.889 --> 26:10.424
(Indistinct conversations)

26:10.426 --> 26:13.460
(Playing jazz)

26:13.462 --> 26:16.730
♪

26:22.204 --> 26:24.472
Okay, this is incredible,
even for Larissa.

26:24.474 --> 26:25.773
They shut down the terminal?

26:25.775 --> 26:27.575
How'd she plan this
in two weeks?

26:27.577 --> 26:28.876
This is what unlimited energy

26:28.878 --> 26:30.945
and an unlimited budget
look like.

26:30.947 --> 26:32.180
Well, looks pretty good.

26:32.182 --> 26:35.049
Oh! Look! There's Bennet
and Walt. (Giggles)

26:35.051 --> 26:36.384
What exactly is Bennet wearing?

26:36.386 --> 26:38.553
- Don't ask.
- Why you're wearing that?

26:38.555 --> 26:40.154
No. Why Walt isn't.
(Chuckles)

26:40.156 --> 26:41.556
Okay, we won't.

26:41.558 --> 26:43.457
I'm giving Larissa away
and marrying them.

26:43.459 --> 26:45.526
- Oh, that's so sweet.
(Walt) - Isn't it?

26:45.528 --> 26:46.894
Her father couldn't be here.

26:46.896 --> 26:48.596
Apparently, being the king
of a tribe is a lot of work,

26:48.598 --> 26:50.197
so she asked me
to stand in his place.

26:50.199 --> 26:52.099
Well, if this is a preview of
what Larissa is going to wear,

26:52.101 --> 26:55.002
I cannot wait. You don't have to.
Larissa needs you.

26:55.004 --> 26:56.570
Well, I need you.

26:56.572 --> 26:58.973
You've gotta convince her
to stop taking muscle relaxers.

26:58.975 --> 27:00.207
So the bride's in usual form?

27:00.209 --> 27:01.342
Pretty much.

27:01.344 --> 27:02.443
You don't mind if I go?

27:02.445 --> 27:04.478
Not at all.
Go save the bride from herself.

27:07.516 --> 27:09.617
Here comes Mr. Bradshaw.

27:09.619 --> 27:12.119
- Walt, good to see you.
- Same.

27:12.121 --> 27:14.622
- Sebastian.
- Hi, sir.

27:14.624 --> 27:16.357
We miss having you
around the house.

27:16.359 --> 27:17.825
So quiet without...

27:17.827 --> 27:20.094
You and Carrie.

27:20.096 --> 27:21.528
Um...

27:21.530 --> 27:24.164
But I guess that's what happens
when people grow up.

27:24.166 --> 27:25.332
Look, Mr. Bradshaw,

27:25.334 --> 27:27.167
I never wanted to come
between you and Carrie.

27:27.169 --> 27:29.036
That was never my intention.

27:29.038 --> 27:31.839
You know what? I should check
if Bennet needs help.

27:31.841 --> 27:34.041
I know, Sebastian.

27:34.043 --> 27:35.909
This isn't about you.
It's about Carrie.

27:35.911 --> 27:38.045
But it's about her happiness,
and we both want that, right?

27:38.047 --> 27:39.613
I know that you're going
out to California

27:39.615 --> 27:44.117
to chase your dream,
but Carrie...

27:44.119 --> 27:47.120
she's not running
towards something.

27:47.122 --> 27:48.622
She's running away...

27:48.624 --> 27:52.292
from her mistakes,
from potential failure,

27:52.294 --> 27:56.229
and... I didn't raise her
to run away.

28:00.268 --> 28:03.337
Okay, this stalking thing
is getting old, fast.

28:03.339 --> 28:05.238
And maybe it seemed romantic
even a week ago,

28:05.240 --> 28:06.540
but now it's the creepy kind...

28:06.542 --> 28:08.775
The stalking kind of stalking.

28:08.777 --> 28:10.744
I know.
I must seem insane.

28:10.746 --> 28:12.813
Yes, you do, and normally
I like insane,

28:12.815 --> 28:14.314
but this is too much.

28:14.316 --> 28:16.249
I told you I didn't wanna
see you again,

28:16.251 --> 28:18.752
and I'm not gonna run away
just because you were here.

28:18.754 --> 28:21.354
You are gonna have to leave
even if I have to fight you.

28:21.356 --> 28:22.455
You're too beautiful to fight.

28:22.457 --> 28:23.623
I am beautiful,

28:23.625 --> 28:25.659
but I'm also strong as hell,
and I will take you.

28:25.661 --> 28:28.862
This place is my safe space.
You need to leave.

28:28.864 --> 28:31.197
You need to go back to your wife
and never come back.

28:31.199 --> 28:33.066
I left my wife.

28:34.135 --> 28:36.102
For you.

28:36.104 --> 28:37.737
For me?

28:37.739 --> 28:41.174
I told Sally
I was in love with you...

28:41.176 --> 28:42.976
which I am.

28:42.978 --> 28:45.512
So what does that mean,
exactly?

28:45.514 --> 28:47.981
I mean, are you looking to have
another open relationship?

28:47.983 --> 28:50.383
Because... I can't believe
I'm saying this...

28:50.385 --> 28:51.451
I don't want that.

28:51.453 --> 28:53.052
I-I don't want that either.

28:53.054 --> 28:56.055
Look, I don't think I was happy
in my relationship

28:56.057 --> 28:57.090
for a long time.

28:57.092 --> 28:59.259
That's why I pushed
for an open marriage.

28:59.261 --> 29:03.596
I was searching
for something...

29:03.598 --> 29:06.766
- something I found with you.
- Oh.

29:10.604 --> 29:13.840
My beautiful shiksa princess,

29:13.842 --> 29:17.009
when I think about love,

29:17.011 --> 29:18.711
I think about planes,

29:18.713 --> 29:22.815
because that is where
we first did the dirty deed.

29:22.817 --> 29:24.317
Oh, no.

29:24.319 --> 29:25.618
I really don't wanna hear this.

29:25.620 --> 29:28.855
You had never joined
the mile high club before.

29:28.857 --> 29:31.257
And I was proud

29:31.259 --> 29:34.961
to open your eyes to sex
in a very small bathroom,

29:34.963 --> 29:38.097
and now every time
I walk through an airport,

29:38.099 --> 29:41.567
I think of you and how one trip

29:41.569 --> 29:44.503
where I practically tore
my hammy...

29:44.505 --> 29:45.838
(Laughs)

29:45.840 --> 29:47.006
Is how we found love.

29:47.008 --> 29:48.507
Oh, I love you, baby.

29:48.509 --> 29:50.276
Don't kiss yet.

29:50.278 --> 29:51.444
Larissa, your vows.

29:51.446 --> 29:52.812
- Oh.
- Oh. (Chuckles)

29:52.814 --> 29:55.381
- Harlan...
- Mm-hmm.

29:55.383 --> 29:57.116
I love this airport.
(Chuckles)

29:57.118 --> 29:58.584
And not just because we did it

29:58.586 --> 30:00.152
in the first class lounge
as well,

30:00.154 --> 30:03.856
but because people come here
running to and fro

30:03.858 --> 30:06.125
to catch flights that will
take them on adventures

30:06.127 --> 30:09.195
to places they've never been,

30:09.197 --> 30:10.596
to see the world...

30:10.598 --> 30:13.265
all things
that I wanna share with you.

30:13.267 --> 30:16.201
But airports aren't
only about leaving.

30:16.203 --> 30:18.337
They're also about
people coming home

30:18.339 --> 30:21.940
to their families,
to their loved ones,

30:21.942 --> 30:26.645
and that's what you are
to me... my family, my home.

30:26.647 --> 30:29.648
We all need a-a place
to come home to,

30:29.650 --> 30:33.752
and in you and this
amazing city, I have found it...

30:33.754 --> 30:35.587
My home.

30:37.524 --> 30:40.526
No. I don't want the “x.”

30:40.528 --> 30:42.094
nothing in the world
that ever happened...

30:42.096 --> 30:44.129
(Door opens and closes) That was
interesting started with “x.”

30:44.131 --> 30:45.497
well, I don't want “q”"

30:45.499 --> 30:48.967
and I want the “m”
and the “w.”

30:48.969 --> 30:51.036
- Are you two idiots still fighting?
- Excuse me, sir,

30:51.038 --> 30:53.538
but we are the best
Castlebury has to offer.

30:53.540 --> 30:54.973
Well, you sure
don't act like it.

31:01.914 --> 31:03.915
Well, now I feel stupid.

31:03.917 --> 31:05.183
Me, too.

31:05.185 --> 31:07.252
Why are we fighting over this?

31:07.254 --> 31:09.187
It's just a bunch of books.

31:09.189 --> 31:13.024
Because... I'm a hideously
competitive person

31:13.026 --> 31:16.027
who pushes the people I love
away.

31:16.029 --> 31:18.663
- No, you don't.
- I pushed you away.

31:19.465 --> 31:21.366
I... can't believe
you didn't run,

31:21.368 --> 31:23.468
screaming for the hills
months before.

31:23.470 --> 31:24.769
You weren't so bad.

31:24.771 --> 31:28.206
Most of the time, I just thought
your intensity was sexy.

31:28.208 --> 31:30.709
And now?

31:30.711 --> 31:32.077
Still sexy.

31:32.079 --> 31:33.645
Oh.

31:36.248 --> 31:39.484
♪

31:47.893 --> 31:51.830
You're not coming, are you?

31:51.832 --> 31:54.632
I want to.

31:54.634 --> 31:56.968
But I can't.

31:59.238 --> 32:02.206
I belong in this city.

32:02.208 --> 32:04.475
This is my home.

32:04.477 --> 32:09.681
And even though there's
nothing for me here...

32:09.683 --> 32:14.118
no job, no college...

32:14.120 --> 32:16.387
I have to stay here

32:16.389 --> 32:19.090
and fight for my life.

32:20.959 --> 32:24.228
And... if I go with you...

32:24.230 --> 32:27.064
You'd just be running away
from your problems

32:27.066 --> 32:28.833
and not embracing your life.

32:30.736 --> 32:32.970
You need to be here.

32:32.972 --> 32:36.173
(Exhales)

32:37.876 --> 32:39.610
(Whispers) I love you.

32:40.712 --> 32:43.147
I'll always love you.

32:46.518 --> 32:48.819
(Crying)

32:48.821 --> 32:50.721
You're gonna be amazing,
Bradshaw.

32:50.723 --> 32:52.323
(Continues crying)

32:52.325 --> 32:55.459
One day, I'm gonna
see your byline

32:55.461 --> 32:57.728
in some magazine or newspaper,

32:57.730 --> 32:59.463
and I'm gonna know
I was lucky enough

32:59.465 --> 33:01.165
to have loved that girl.

33:01.167 --> 33:05.603
Oh... if we're doing
the right thing,

33:05.605 --> 33:08.372
why does it hurt so much?

33:08.374 --> 33:10.708
I don't know.

33:10.710 --> 33:12.409
I don't know.

33:21.152 --> 33:23.020
(Whispers) I should go.

33:25.523 --> 33:26.590
Yeah.

33:26.592 --> 33:30.694
I don't wanna make you late
for your flight.

33:33.932 --> 33:39.736
(Crying)

33:39.738 --> 33:41.238
Bye, Bradshaw.

33:41.240 --> 33:44.341
Good-bye, Kydd.

33:47.779 --> 33:50.313
<i>That's when I realized</i>
<i>it isn't good-bye</i>

33:50.315 --> 33:51.948
<i>because it feels wonderful.</i>

33:51.950 --> 33:53.116
(Continues crying)

33:53.118 --> 33:55.919
<i>It's good-bye because</i>
<i>it feels so final,</i>

33:55.921 --> 33:57.721
<i>like maybe it's for good.</i>

34:02.113 --> 34:04.714
♪

34:04.716 --> 34:08.184
(Indistinct conversations)

34:08.186 --> 34:10.053
(Harlan speaks indistinctly,
laughs)

34:10.054 --> 34:11.888
I am happy, Tommy boy.

34:11.889 --> 34:14.123
Oh. I'm happy for you.
(Glasses clink)

34:14.126 --> 34:15.792
Mmm.

34:15.793 --> 34:18.628
♪

34:18.630 --> 34:20.597
Ah, okay, enough already.

34:20.599 --> 34:24.801
So she's not staying
in New York. Big deal.

34:24.803 --> 34:28.271
Or going to college or finding
a way to make a living.

34:28.273 --> 34:30.473
Well, at least she's not
in rehab like George.

34:30.475 --> 34:32.208
Yeah, that's why he's not here.

34:32.210 --> 34:33.976
Apparently the kid
can't handle his liquor

34:33.978 --> 34:35.344
or his drugs.

34:35.347 --> 34:37.192
Sometimes I wonder
if he's mine.

34:37.312 --> 34:40.812
(Laughs) I'm sorry man.
That must be hard.

34:42.120 --> 34:45.521
Eh. I've been
a lousy parent.

34:45.523 --> 34:50.025
Made my life all about me,
not about him.

34:50.027 --> 34:53.096
Well, I did the opposite,
and what did I get for it?

34:53.098 --> 34:54.429
A great kid.

34:56.199 --> 34:57.567
So what?

34:57.569 --> 34:59.469
So she's a little lost.

34:59.471 --> 35:01.637
That's part of growing up...

35:01.639 --> 35:04.240
becoming someone interesting.

35:04.242 --> 35:06.375
Let her know

35:06.377 --> 35:08.010
when it gets bad...

35:08.012 --> 35:09.979
She has you to run to.

35:11.148 --> 35:15.151
The girl introduced me
to my gorgeous bride.

35:15.153 --> 35:16.819
Don't let her leave thinking

35:16.821 --> 35:19.722
she isn't the gem that she is.

35:19.724 --> 35:22.191
You're a good man, Harlan.

35:22.193 --> 35:23.851
Yeah, I'm softening
in my old age.

35:23.971 --> 35:27.139
Or maybe...
It's what love does.

35:27.259 --> 35:28.241
(Scoffs)

35:29.901 --> 35:34.436
♪

35:34.438 --> 35:35.504
I'm so sorry.

35:35.506 --> 35:36.906
Do you mind if I interrupt

35:36.908 --> 35:39.308
and get a dance
with my daughter?

35:39.310 --> 35:40.910
Oh, no, no, not at all.

35:40.912 --> 35:42.878
I'm gonna go find my husband.

35:42.880 --> 35:46.448
Oh. I love the sound of that...
“husband.”

35:46.450 --> 35:48.517
(chuckles) (Chuckles)

35:52.822 --> 35:55.424
I remember when
you were a little girl,

35:55.426 --> 35:57.593
and you loved dancing.

35:57.595 --> 35:59.428
I mean, anytime we were
at a party or a wedding,

35:59.430 --> 36:02.197
you never wanted
me and your mom to dance...

36:02.199 --> 36:03.232
Just you and I.

36:03.234 --> 36:05.734
Yeah, no wonder
I have so many issues.

36:05.736 --> 36:07.469
Oh, it was sweet.

36:07.471 --> 36:09.838
You'd put your feet
on top of mine,

36:09.840 --> 36:12.274
and we would waltz.

36:12.276 --> 36:14.209
I think I remember that.

36:14.211 --> 36:15.410
Yeah. And I just...

36:15.412 --> 36:17.813
It's just hard to believe that

36:17.815 --> 36:20.349
that little girl's
all grown up.

36:20.351 --> 36:21.984
♪

36:21.986 --> 36:25.253
And that she's leaving.

36:25.255 --> 36:27.723
Dad, I'm not going.

36:27.725 --> 36:32.928
This city is where I belong.

36:32.930 --> 36:34.429
But... but...

36:34.431 --> 36:36.031
I don't have a lot of answers.

36:36.033 --> 36:37.732
Well, any, really.

36:37.734 --> 36:42.537
All I know is that
I have screwed up royally.

36:42.539 --> 36:44.306
But I'm here

36:44.308 --> 36:46.908
to fight for the life
that I want in this city

36:46.910 --> 36:48.243
as a writer.

36:48.245 --> 36:50.679
And I'm not gonna ask you
for a dime.

36:50.681 --> 36:53.949
I will find a place to live.
I'll find freelance jobs.

36:53.951 --> 36:56.051
I'll try my hand
at waitressing.

36:56.053 --> 36:58.019
Whatever it takes to make it.

36:58.021 --> 37:00.188
And you don't have to worry
about me.

37:00.190 --> 37:02.557
I promise.

37:02.559 --> 37:04.225
♪

37:04.227 --> 37:06.061
I'll always worry about you,

37:06.063 --> 37:09.397
because you'll always
be my kid.

37:14.637 --> 37:16.838
<i>Sometimes to chase after</i>
<i>your future,</i>

37:16.840 --> 37:18.206
<i>you have to stop running</i>

37:18.208 --> 37:20.441
<i>and plant yourself</i>
<i>in one place.</i>

37:20.443 --> 37:24.946
<i>Take a stand</i>
<i>and fight for what you want...</i>

37:28.884 --> 37:31.853
<i>and know that even after</i>
<i>the darkest of nights,</i>

37:31.855 --> 37:34.055
<i>the dawn will come.</i>

37:37.126 --> 37:41.162
<i>And you will find a place</i>
<i>where you don't have to hide.</i>

37:47.469 --> 37:50.037
<i>A place to call home.</i>

37:52.808 --> 37:55.076
This is nice...
Breakfast at the diner.

37:55.078 --> 37:56.978
It's what we used to do.

37:56.980 --> 37:59.514
Maybe those encyclopedias
aren't so bad after all.

37:59.516 --> 38:01.515
But I really don't want them.

38:01.517 --> 38:05.486
Me, either.
They're so big and heavy.

38:05.488 --> 38:08.322
And it's not like
Harvard doesn't have them.

38:08.324 --> 38:09.757
Should we donate them
to the high school?

38:09.759 --> 38:11.559
I like that idea.

38:14.229 --> 38:15.496
I'm really glad

38:15.498 --> 38:18.299
this is the way
we are saying good-bye.

38:18.301 --> 38:19.867
Me, too.

38:22.637 --> 38:25.172
Why don't you just do
your laundry at the base?

38:25.174 --> 38:26.373
They use too much starch.

38:26.375 --> 38:28.909
And I like the way
your soap smells.

38:28.911 --> 38:30.244
It reminds me of you.

38:30.246 --> 38:32.980
It's like you're with me
even when we're not together.

38:32.982 --> 38:35.049
You don't have to do this,
you know.

38:35.051 --> 38:36.383
Huh?

38:36.385 --> 38:37.985
I mean, you don't have to act
all romantic all the time.

38:37.987 --> 38:39.019
I don't expect anything.

38:39.021 --> 38:40.688
I mean, I do.
I expect a lot,

38:40.690 --> 38:43.590
and I deserve it, too, but it
doesn't have to be with you.

38:43.592 --> 38:46.527
I don't think
I'm following here.

38:46.529 --> 38:48.562
I know about Jess.

38:48.564 --> 38:51.732
♪

38:51.734 --> 38:53.000
Maggie, I can explain...

38:53.002 --> 38:54.268
This... this is why
you were so cagey

38:54.270 --> 38:55.803
when I asked about
your plans for the fall...

38:55.805 --> 38:57.504
Because you were gonna
break up with me by then?

38:57.506 --> 38:59.573
You don't understand.
Jess isn't a girl.

38:59.575 --> 39:00.607
Uh, I talked to her.

39:00.609 --> 39:02.309
She hung up on me
when I asked about you.

39:02.311 --> 39:03.744
Walt was with me.

39:03.746 --> 39:06.013
I mean, she is,
but she's not a girl to me.

39:06.015 --> 39:09.416
She... works
at a jewelry store.

39:09.418 --> 39:10.617
Oh, and instead of cards,

39:10.619 --> 39:12.319
they give out napkins
with their numbers on it?

39:12.321 --> 39:14.054
Yeah. I'm not buying.

39:14.056 --> 39:16.390
(Sighs) Jess' husband,
who I bunk with,

39:16.392 --> 39:18.191
wrote her number down
so that I could call her

39:18.193 --> 39:21.028
to get something...
for you.

39:21.030 --> 39:24.231
Okay, wait. If you got me
something, where is it?

39:24.233 --> 39:27.334
<i>♪</i>

39:27.336 --> 39:29.169
(Sighs)

39:29.171 --> 39:30.437
(Unzips bag)

39:30.439 --> 39:34.441
<i>♪</i>

39:36.210 --> 39:38.778
Here it is.

39:38.780 --> 39:41.581
Are you... are you...
are you proposing... to me?

39:41.583 --> 39:43.950
I wanted to do it in
a nice restaurant or something,

39:43.952 --> 39:47.354
but... yes, I am.

39:47.356 --> 39:49.623
Look, I know we haven't been
together that long,

39:49.625 --> 39:51.224
but I feel like
when you know, you know,

39:51.226 --> 39:52.459
and I know.

39:52.461 --> 39:56.930
I wanna spend the rest
of my life with you.

39:58.766 --> 40:00.533
And I was trying
to change the subject

40:00.535 --> 40:01.868
about our plans for the fall

40:01.870 --> 40:04.037
because I was hoping,
if you said “yes,”

40:04.039 --> 40:06.639
we'd be living together
in our own quarters.

40:08.409 --> 40:11.444
- But maybe this is too soon?
- Yes.

40:11.446 --> 40:13.546
- It is. Uh, you're not ready.
- Yes.

40:13.548 --> 40:14.981
No, no, no, no.
I mean, I mean,

40:14.983 --> 40:16.616
I mean, no, it's not too soon.
Yes, yes. I say yes!

40:16.618 --> 40:18.051
I say yes, I say yes.

40:18.053 --> 40:19.452
(Chuckles)

40:23.958 --> 40:25.191
(Exhales deeply)

40:25.193 --> 40:27.126
Hi.

40:27.128 --> 40:31.497
Um...
I have some surprising news.

40:31.499 --> 40:33.499
Can I see you?

40:33.501 --> 40:36.302
(Knock on door)

40:37.471 --> 40:40.339
Okay, Bambi.
You better start dishin'.

40:44.411 --> 40:46.212
I'm staying,

40:46.214 --> 40:49.615
and Larissa agreed to let me
sublet her place.

40:49.617 --> 40:51.184
Well, this is
a hell of a lot better

40:51.186 --> 40:52.818
than the places I'm looking at.

40:52.820 --> 40:56.822
Well, at 550 bucks,
I can't afford it on my own.

40:56.824 --> 41:00.826
So... I was thinking maybe
if I had a roommate?

41:00.828 --> 41:02.128
Are you thinking me?

41:02.130 --> 41:03.763
'Cause I know last time
we tried this,

41:03.765 --> 41:05.298
it didn't work out so well.

41:05.300 --> 41:07.166
Well, I think we'll be fine,

41:07.168 --> 41:10.403
as long as you don't try
and share my underwear.

41:10.405 --> 41:13.039
Oh, I stopped wearing underwear,
so it shouldn't be a problem.

41:13.041 --> 41:15.341
(Chuckles) Of course you did.

41:15.343 --> 41:18.778
So what do you say?
You and me? Living together?

41:18.780 --> 41:20.946
Honey, I'm in.

41:20.948 --> 41:22.448
(Simple Minds'
“Alive And Kicking” playing)

41:22.450 --> 41:23.549
(Laughs)

41:23.551 --> 41:24.750
♪ Alive and kicking ♪

41:24.752 --> 41:27.052
<i>They say running</i>
<i>is a solitary endeavor.</i>

41:27.054 --> 41:29.755
♪ Stay until your love is ♪

41:29.757 --> 41:30.956
<i>But not for me.</i>

41:30.958 --> 41:34.193
<i>Being together</i>
<i>as we chased our dreams</i>

41:34.195 --> 41:36.996
<i>made the ups and downs</i>
<i>just a little bit better.</i>

41:36.998 --> 41:39.565
♪ Oh, ba-da-da-da ♪

41:39.567 --> 41:42.568
♪ ba-ba-da-da-da ♪

41:42.570 --> 41:44.970
(Cheering)

41:44.972 --> 41:49.007
<i>And this was the group</i>
<i>I wanted to run with.</i>

41:49.009 --> 41:51.009
♪ Ba-da-da-da ♪

41:51.011 --> 41:53.979
♪ alive and kicking ♪

41:53.981 --> 41:56.482
♪ oh, stay until your love is ♪

